ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Large, or black, cardamom (_Amomum subulatum_; _Zingiberaceae_) is native to the Eastern Himalayas growing in cool, moist forest areas. It is a clustering plant with flower buds appearing from the base of the rhizome. Black cardamom is an important commercial crop in parts of India's Darjeeling hills, Bhutan, and Nepal. Typically, cultivation occurs in woodland areas with overhead shade and access to regular irrigation.

There is also another type of cardamom (_Elettaria cardamomum_; _Zingiberaceae_) called small, lesser, true, Malabar or green cardamom, which is an Indian native growing in tropical areas. Both black and green cardamom are highly prized spices.

_Glomerella cingulata_ (previously _Colletotrichum gloeosporioides_) is the main pathogen associated with anthracnose and blight diseases in many crops. Symptoms often include rapidly expanding brown/black leaf lesions, necrosis, defoliation, tuber rots, and dieback of entire plants. Disease development is usually favoured by humid conditions. Economic losses are due to reduced yield and severe reduction of product quality before and after harvest.

The fungus is spread mainly by infected plant material (including seeds and tubers) mechanical means (including human and insect activity) and splashing rain. It has a long saprophytic survival ability on crop residues. Disease management may include use of clean planting material, cultural techniques (including crop rotation or fallow periods between crops), phytosanitation and resistant varieties, if available. Fungicides may help to delay the onset of epidemics in some crops, but usually cannot prevent their development.

A leaf blight of black cardamom was first reported from India in the early 1980s, which was later described as anthracnose caused by _G. cingulata_. The pathogen was shown to be associated with an outbreak of cardamom leaf and sheath blight in 2006 in various districts of Sikkim and Darjeeling Hills (Saju et al, 2013, Journal of Spices and Aromatic Crops 22, 101-3) and has since become economically important for the region.

